   "source": [
    "# Time Series Wind Roses\n",
    "\n",
    "When dealing with Air Quality Time Series, it is important to assess how distributions are affected by Wind Direction.\n",
    "\n",
    "The Weather Toolbox provides a Wind object to ease such analysis.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Introduction\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "### Imports\n",
    "\n",
    "We import required packages:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "from odapi.connectors import Irceline\n",
    "from odapi.toolbox import Wind"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from odapi.settings import settings\n",
    "settings.logger.setLevel(40)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Dataset & Client\n",
    "\n",
    "We load the dataset we previously stored and create the Irceline client:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "data = pd.read_pickle(\"dump/brussels_2014.pickle\").droplevel([1,2,3], axis=1)\n",
    "client = Irceline()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Roses and Boxplots\n",
    "\n",
    "We will perform our analysis on the following series:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "skeys = ['NO/41R001 (µg/m³)', 'PM-2.5/41N043 (µg/m³)', 'CO2/41R002 (ppm)',\n",
    "          'O3/41R012 (µg/m³)', 'T/41R001 (°C)', 'WS/41R001 (m/s)']"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Note:** There is a difference between Goniometric and Trigonometric systems. By defaults, Weather methods expect to get Goniometric angles (common meteorological reference) instead of Trigonometric angles."
   ]
  },

   ],
   "source": [
    "scales = client.scales()\n",
    "for k in skeys:\n",
    "    axe1 = Wind.boxplot(data, k, theta='WD/41R001 (°G)')\n",
    "    axe1[0].set_ylim(scales[k.split('/')[0]])\n",
    "    axe2 = Wind.rose(data, k, theta='WD/41R001 (°G)')\n",
    "    axe2.set_ylim(scales[k.split('/')[0]])"
   ]
